Project: Wrangle and Analyze Data¶

by Ryan S.

Introduction¶

The dataset that you will be wrangling (and analyzing and visualizing) is the tweet archive of Twitter user @dog_rates, also known as WeRateDogs. WeRateDogs is a Twitter account that rates people's dogs with a humorous comment about the dog. These ratings almost always have a denominator of 10. The numerators, though? Almost always greater than 10. 11/10, 12/10, 13/10, etc. Why? Because "they're good dogs Brent." WeRateDogs has over 4 million followers and has received international media coverage.

WeRateDogs downloaded their Twitter archive and sent it to Udacity via email exclusively for you to use in this project. This archive contains basic tweet data (tweet ID, timestamp, text, etc.) for all 5000+ of their tweets as they stood on August 1, 2017.

Your goal: wrangle WeRateDogs Twitter data to create interesting and trustworthy analyses and visualizations. The Twitter archive is great, but it only contains very basic tweet information. Additional gathering, then assessing and cleaning is required for "Wow!"-worthy analyses and visualizations.

Once completed, create a 300-600 word written report called 'wrangle_report' that briefly describes your wrangling efforts. This is to be framed as an internal document.

Assessing¶

In this section, I will be looking at quality and tidiness issues.

Quality issues are content issues; the data is considered low quality or "dirty". There are four dimensions that I am considering when assessing this data:

  1. Completeness - This is concerned with missing data; rows, columns, and cells
  2. Validity - This is concerend with the data conforming to a schema or contstraints, like the correct format for a date/time
  3. Accuracy - This is concerned with the data being inaccurate but still valid
  4. Consistency - This is concerned with the same data being displayed in different ways, but one way has to be chosen

Tidiness issues are structural issues; the data is considered "messy". It depends on how rows, columns, and tables are matched up with observations, variables, and types. There three basic requirements:

  1. Each variable forms a column
  2. Each observation forms a row
  3. Each type of observational unit forms a table


There are three datasets I will be assessing:

  • ta = Twitter archive data
  • ip = Image prediction data
  • td = Tweet data

I am breaking my assessment out by each dataset first, then I will combine the complete findings at the end of the assessment.

Observations:¶

There are 5 columns with over 92% null values. Four of them end in _id and the small number of rows that are not null all have scientific notation values, which is likely incorrect. These datatypes may need to be changed, but if you change them, the question becomes: will the values be correct? The follow up question is, how important are these fields for what you want to do with the data?

  • tweet_id, timestamp, text all have the same number of unique values as there are rows, so no duplicates in those fields.
  • There are 137 rows that have duplicated data in the expanded_url column.
  • I need to check the expanded_urls column to see why there are duplicates and why there are null values.
  • I need to check the values in the name column. There seems to be some odd words, and there is some case issues.
  • The last four columns have only 2 values each, and since I can visually see values of 'None' there is only one over possible value. I'll need to check what those values are and how many.
  • Look at source to see if anything needs to be done with it.

Source¶

The source column has a html code in it, and this probably isn't necessary, so I want to find out what is in this code.

In [107]:
# Shows the value counts of the values in the source column
ta.source.value_counts()
Out[107]:
<a href="http://twitter.com/download/iphone" rel="nofollow">Twitter for iPhone</a>     2221
<a href="http://vine.co" rel="nofollow">Vine - Make a Scene</a>                        91  
<a href="http://twitter.com" rel="nofollow">Twitter Web Client</a>                     33  
<a href="https://about.twitter.com/products/tweetdeck" rel="nofollow">TweetDeck</a>    11  
Name: source, dtype: int64

Observations:

This is pretty straightforward. There are only four different html links in the source column. These represent the application used to post the tweet, either the Twitter iPhone app, Vine app, the Twitter web page itself, or a website/application called Tweetdeck. The html code is not needed.

Quality (dirty data) – missing content, corrupted data, duplicate data, or incorrect data¶

  • tweet_id is an integer
  • timestamp is a string
  • There are duplicate values in the expanded_url column (66)
  • There are null values in the expanded_url column (59)
  • name column: some rows have 'None', some rows have non-names such as "a, an, quite..."
  • There are 109 rows with lowercase values using 25 different words in the name column
  • Tweet 671542985629241344 needs to have the name field corrected to "O'Malley"
  • The value of "None" appears 745 times in the name column
  • There are a lot of "None" values in the doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo columns
  • Columns ending in _id have a 92% or higher null rate
  • Columns ending in _id have scientific notations in rows that aren't null (like 8.102541e+17)
  • There are rows what have numerators and/or denominators that are too high or too low for the scale
  • There are 2286 rows that contain a tiny URL or part of a tiny URL at the end; 70 rows do not
  • There are 54 rows that contain the html code &amp for an ampersand
  • There are 95 rows that contain at least one \n which is code for a new line
  • source column: The column contains html code that is not needed

Tidiness (messy data) – structural issues¶

  • expanded_urls column: some rows have more than one URL and/or duplicate URLs
  • dog stages are split into 4 columns

P1 Columns Observations:¶

  • There is a mix of cases in the words in the p1 column; some low, some capitalized, and some a mix
  • There are no uppercase only words in the p1 column
  • There are 298 different lowercase words in 1135 rows in the p1 column
  • Not all lowercase words are dogs; many are other objects--I believe this is intentional to be "funny"
  • There are 80 different capital case words in 940 rows. This includes the words that are both capitalized and a mix;
    • Examples: 'German_shepherd', 'Chesapeake_Bay_retriever', 'Saint_Bernard'
  • the p1_conf column is filled with confidence interval numbers that are float64 data type
    • No value appears more than twice
      • Single values appear 1937 times
      • Values of 2 appear 69 times
    • The highest confidence interval is 1.0
  • The p1_dog column contains 1532 'True' values, and 543 'False' values

I need to figure out if the different cases in the p1 column are an issue or can stay the same. At a minimum I should either make them all lowercase or capitalize the first letter for consistency.

P2 Columns Observations:¶

  • There is a mix of cases in the words in the p2 column; some low, some capitalized, and some a mix
  • There are no uppercase only words in the p2 column
  • There are 321 different lowercase words in 1096 rows in the p2 column
  • Not all lowercase words are dogs; many are other objects--I believe this is intentional to be "funny"
  • There are 84 different capital case words in 979 rows. This includes the words that are both capitalized and a mix;
    • Examples: 'German_shepherd', 'Chesapeake_Bay_retriever', 'Saint_Bernard'
  • The p2_conf column is filled with confidence interval numbers that are float64 data type
    • No value appears more than twice
      • Single values appear 1934 times
      • Values of 2 appear 69 times
      • Values of 3 appear once
    • The highest confidence interval is 0.4880140000000001
  • The p2_dog column contains 1553 'True' values, and 522 'False' values

Assessment Summary¶

Note: There are some issues noted below that get resolved when another issue is resolved without any additional work needed. All issues do get resolved.

Quality¶

Twitter Archive Data:

  • tweet_id is data type integer and should be string
  • timestamp is data type string and should be datetime
  • expanded_url column: There are duplicate values (66)
  • expanded_url column: There are null values (59)
  • name column: There a lot rows that contain 'None' instead of null
  • name column: There are rows with lowercase values in the name column that are non-names such as "a, an, quite..." (109)
  • Tweet 671542985629241344 needs to have the name field corrected to "O'Malley"
  • There are a lot of "None" values in the doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo columns that should be NaN
  • The doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo columns should be merged into one column with those four possible values plus null (currently "None" and needs to be changed to null)
  • Instructed to only include original ratings, so rows with ...reply... or ...retweeted... values can be dropped
  • Columns with ...reply... or ...retweeted... can be dropped as well since we aren't using them and they would all be NaN after dropping rows
  • There are numerators that are too high because people were rating groups of dogs instead of individual dogs; these will need to be dropped
  • There are denominators that are too high because people were rating groups of dogs instead of individual dogs; those rows will need to be dropped
  • There are 3 denominators that are less than 10 and those rows will also need to be dropped
  • text column: There are 2286 rows that contain a tiny URL or part of a tiny URL at the end; 70 rows do not
  • text column: There are 54 rows that contain the html code &amp for an ampersand
  • text column: There are 95 rows that contain at least one \n which is code for a new line
  • text column: There are rows that contain at least one \r which is code for a carriage return
  • source column: The column contains html code that is not needed

Image Prediction Data:

  • tweet_id is an integer and should be string
  • The jpg_url column contains duplicates; the same amount as expanded_urls in the ta dataset
  • Columns p1, p2, and p3 have a mix of words that are both capitalized and a mix
    • Examples: 'German_shepherd', 'Chesapeake_Bay_retriever', 'Saint_Bernard'
  • Some values in columns p1, p2, and p3 contain underscores


Tweet Data:

  • tweet_id is an integer and should be string
  • Duplicate values in the favorites and retweets columns

Tidiness Issues¶

  • All three datasets should be joined into one master dataset, but not all columns are needed

    • The image predictions dataset has 281 fewer rows than the Twitter archive dataset
    • The tweet data dataset has 2 fewer rows than the Twitter archive dataset

  • ta dataset: dog stages are split into 4 columns

  • The created_at column has too much info in one cell and should be split out and reformatted, but can be dropped instead since we have the necessary data in the timestamp column and it is already formatted correctly

  • There are rows that have more than one URL in the expanded_urls column; some are identical, some have different domains

Missing Data¶

Define - Merging and Dropping Non-Intersecting Rows¶

The image prediction data has 281 fewer rows than the Twitter archive data. Since there is no way for me to get those missing rows of data, those extra rows in the archive data will be left out. Simply merging the two will "drop" those extra rows. I will also merge the tweet data with these, which will "drop" an additional two rows. This is simultaneously a tidiness issue.

Code¶

In [239]:
# Merging the datasets and simultaneously removing missing data
merged = pd.merge(ta, ip, on = ['tweet_id'] )
merged = pd.merge(merged, td, on = ['tweet_id'])
In [240]:
# Saving the complete merged dataset as is without additional cleaning
merged.to_csv('merged.csv', encoding = 'utf-8')

Define - Melting Columns¶

The dog stages are split into 4 columns: doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo. These should all be in one column with these four possible values, or None. I'm going to create some variables and use list comprehension and melt to accomplish this.

Code¶

In [247]:
# Setting up columns to melt
to_melt = ['doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper', 'puppo']
In [248]:
# Setting up columns to keep
to_keep = [x for x in list(df.columns) if x not in to_melt]
In [249]:
# Melt the columns into a single new column
df = pd.melt(df, 
             id_vars = to_keep, 
             value_vars = to_melt, 
             var_name = 'stages', 
             value_name = 'dog_stage')
In [250]:
# Drop the stages column because it is not needed
df = df.drop('stages', axis=1)
In [251]:
# The melt created a lot of duplicate rows, this drops them
df = df.sort_values('dog_stage').drop_duplicates('tweet_id', keep = 'last')

Define - Replacing expanded_urls with a New Column¶

The expanded_urls column is an issue to me. There are a lot of rows that contain multiple urls, some of which are the same twitter status url repeated twice or more, some are the twitter status url combined with a url from another domain, such as 'gofundme.com'. I could not find a good way to split these out into columns because cells contain differing amounts of urls and it wants a specific number of columns provided when you do a str.split, otherwise it will fail and say you don't have enough values for the columns, or you don't have enough columns.

Since the urls all contain the same domain as a string and then use the tweet_id, I can just create a new column and use a for loop to fill it with the string and the tweet_id. There is a caveat though; most urls end with .../photo/1, but there are 78 that end in .../video/1. This can be isolated by using the jpg_url path:

  • If the path contains media or tweet_video_thumb then expanded_urls ends with .../photo/1
  • If the path contains ext_tw_video_thumb then expanded_urls ends with .../video/1

This will have to be done in two steps; once for the urls that end in photo and once for the urls that end in video, and then concatenate them. Once that is complete I will drop the expanded_urls column.

Univariate Exploration¶

Source Data¶

In [375]:
df.source.value_counts()
Out[375]:
iPhone       1911
Twitter      28  
Tweetdeck    10  
Name: source, dtype: int64

This shows the data has a flaw; there is no Android app as one of the sources of this data. Android has a larger market share than iPhone, so we are potentially missing a lot of data. If I were going to go further with this data, I'd either want to find some Android data to bring in, or drop the Twitter and Tweetdeck data and just focus on the iPhone data. I also suspect there's probably a lot more people using Twitter and Tweetdeck than this dataset shows.

Prediction Data¶

I do not trust the prediction data because I spot checked quite a few and I saw quite a few errors, even with a decent confidence interval. But I am going to go on the assumption that we trust the data.

I am setting the standard that I'm only going to work with data that has a 50% or higher confidence interval.

Bivariate Analysis¶

Favorites vs Retweets¶

I want to compare favorites and retweets to see how they align. However, since they are so severely skewed, I am going to change them to a log10 scale.

In [394]:
log = df.copy()
In [395]:
log['favorites'] = np.log10(log['favorites'])
In [396]:
log['retweets'] = np.log10(log['retweets'])
In [397]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
sns.set(style="darkgrid", font_scale=1.5)
sns.distplot(log.favorites, color="red", label="Favorites");
sns.distplot(log.retweets, color="cornflowerblue", label="Retweets");
plt.title('Favorites and Retweets Counts Using Log10')
plt.legend();
plt.xlabel('');

Favorites and Retweets have similar distributions when scaled to log10. Recall, however, that their 75th percentile is quite different; around 3200 for retweets, while favorites were close to 11,500.
